        "Brief": {
          "id": "theory",
          "title": "Theory:",
          "brief_html": "<p>In $\\mathbb{Z}/m\\mathbb{Z}$, the inverse of $a$ is an integer $x$ such that $ax \\equiv 1 \\pmod m$.</p>\n<p>An inverse exists <strong>if and only if</strong> $\\gcd(a,m)=1$. When $\\gcd(a,m)\\neq 1$, no inverse exists (e.g. $2 \\pmod 4$).</p>\n<p>The Extended Euclidean Algorithm finds integers $u,v$ with $au+bv=\\gcd(a,b)$. When $\\gcd(a,m)=1$, reducing $au+bv=1 \\pmod m$ gives $au \\equiv 1 \\pmod m$, so $u$ is the inverse.</p>\n<p>Visualizations from the original notebook (clock face mod 7, gcd heatmap) are described in the curriculum theory section.</p>\n"
        }
      },
